DROPSET - what is it? 
Dropset - simply meaning you’ll drop (decrease) weight during a set. 🔘 HOW? Start with a fairly heavy weight and do as many reps you can. When you feel like you can’t do another rep with that heavy weight, you can still keep going with a lower weight to really make your muscles tired. 🔸 Most common is to lower the weight 3-4 times during one set (you’ll see me using 3 different weights here) but you can drop as many times as you want. 🔘 WHEN is dropset a good idea? At the end of your weight lifting session to squeeze out the last drop of energy in your muscles. When you have limited time to work out. When you’ve reached a plateau and need to switch it up, or simply in your workout schedule to add something new and interesting. 
Hope this was helpful! 💗

Please read caption 🚨 Training with ’only’ bodyweight can be a real challenge! It often feels like the workout is pretty useless because you’re used to lifting kilo after kilo in the gym, right? 

It doesn’t have to be useless if you pick the right exercises! 

What do I mean by that? 
Well, some exercises are really challenging only by the movement and do not require a lot (or any!) weight to be tough even for the most badass gymrat! Here are some of my BEST picks for bodyweight glutes that are tough and effective!

1️⃣ Single Leg Glute Bridge. Brutal! I like to angle my working leg/knee slightly outward to get a ’scoop’ movement. This is my go to exercise when on vacation! 
2️⃣. Pulse Split Squats. Split squats are always brutal, and one way to make them even more challenging when you can’t use the weight as overload is to add pulses and slow down the movement. (This video is speeded up by 1,5). 
3️⃣. Side Abduction Bridge. The QUEEN of upper glute bodyweight movements! I can push the whole weight stack of the abduction machine in the gym, yet I feel this is SO challenging only after 8-10-12 reps!!
4️⃣. Step Ups - Studies show this is one of the movements where the glute muscles are most active! It's also very challenging without any weight.
5️⃣. Reverse Hypers - An upside down glute bridge, perfect to isolate your glutes. Keep pumping, I promise this will be challenging after a few sets! 

🤍 Hope you like these tips! 
Ps: These shorts will be available at @stacciathletics in November! They’re so good I can’t even.. 👀 #stacciathletics

My full story with cancer. Still hard to talk about but I feel like it’s my responsibility. Not a single day goes by without a DM from someone who has questions about my cancer story, and for my OG followers, you’ve probably seen these clips and heard this story before, but anyway, here we go. 

I detected a swollen lymph node on one side of my neck in late 2013 and immediately got worried because my grandma died from lymphoma before I was born. They say it’s a cancer that does not run in the family but who really knows.. 

I got it checked pretty immediately and every single doctor told me I shouldn't worry, that I’m too young to have cancer (I was 26), that it’s normal to have swollen lymph nodes so on and so on. 

They told me to go home and wait. I couldn’t. I literally harassed them every other day until they did a biopsy. First with a thin needle - nothing detected. Then with a thick needle - nothing detected. Then I had an open surgery where I was awake and they were soooo deep into my neck I was horrified. They removed a large portion of the lymph node but came back with no indication of cancer. 

At this time it was so big you could clearly see it just by looking at me and now I wanted it out because I couldn’t stand the look of it. So I went into another surgery, this time asleep. It never been anesthetized before so I didn’t really know what to expect. I woke up couple hours later with tubes coming out of my neck full of blood - pretty terrifying tbh. At this time I didn’t think I had cancer tough because of all the previous tests. 

When the doctor called me a week or so later with the results I tried to reschedule the meeting because I didn’t think it was serious and we were redoing our apartment and I needed to be at home. He then said I should come to the blood department and then I got so scared (still didn’t think I had cancer) but I could feel it was something serious. 

** CONTINUES IN COMMENTS**

How deep are your squats❓As close to ’ass-to-the-grass’ you can,  I hope? Then why not level up and get your lunges to that same range of motion to make them even more effective?! 

❕A regular lunge movement allows you to mimic a 90 dregree squat (approximately). 
❕If you put your front foot on something elevated like a weight plate, you will create a greater range of motion, make your glutes and legs work harder, for a longer time under tension - making your lunge slightly more effective! Try first by holding one kettlebell/dumbbell infront of your chest or on straight arm, then advance to two (straight arm)! Promise you’ll feel this one!

Who’s ready to try this the next time lunges shows up in your workout schedule?

🎵 Song: DJ Khaled - I did it (ft. Post Malone)

node.text:
Flat stomach? Tiny waist? Six pack? 🥵🤞 A common mistake is to workout your abs everyday in hope of making them more visible. That is counter productive! Your abdominal muscles work just as your other muscles, to grow you need challenging workouts, nutritional food, rest & recovery. 

The key for muscle growth is workload, consistency and rest for recovery - always! 
That being said, I have to touch the topic of question I get almost daily: How to AVOID getting a squared waist. 

Many women fear the look of a ”crossfit core” (super muscular and often squared) - Let me tell you, you would have to work out like a MF to get that kind of a core to start with so don’t worry, haha. Crossfit is performance, ’bodybuilding’ is aesthetic (It also has a lot of performance benefits ofc but it’s not the main focus). 

When you work your abs, focus on FORM and not how much weight you’re pushing. Why is this important? Because you should involve your TVA muscle to keep your core tight. The RA is the muscle you SEE, but the TVA is what helps you keep your core nice and tight. 

You can do exercises that focus solidly on your TVA (like dead bugs, belly vacuum and so on) but what I personally think is more important is to involve TVA as much as possible in the ab-exercise that allows it, or actually, in every exercise not only ab-ones! 

Okay, so how do you do that? Have you ever heard ”keep your core tight and try not to arch your back”, if you follow any of my plans I’m 100% sure you’re tired of me telling you that LOL! Think as if you’re sucking your belly button in towards your spine and keep it there by squeezing. Before an exercise stand up tall and suck you belly button in but KEEP BREATHING - once you find that form, implement it in this workout: 

1️⃣ Reverse Crunch Twist 
2️⃣ DB sit up 
3️⃣ Shoulder Taps 
4️⃣ Toe Reach 
🤍4 sets, 10-15 reps each. 
LETS GO team! Come work out with me through @athli.team 🤍💗🤍

node.text:
❗️Why you NEED to combine these two movements for glute gains: 

Okey listen up!
👀 Lunge/squat movements emphasize on your lower glutes and give most tension at a fully stretched position meaning when your glute muscle is stretched. 

👀 Thrust/bridge movements on the other hand emphasize on your upper glutes and give most tension at a contracted position. 

So if you’re looking to FULLY target your gluteus max, these movements should be combined in your workout schedule!  Of course, I got you covered when doing any of my workout plans on @athli.team.

🤍 Tap like if you like easy & informative posts like this. 
🤍 outfits @stacciathletics 
Lots of lovvveee!

node.text:
Can you guess the weight difference in these two pics? I’ll tell you the answer soon! 

Why is this important? Because we need to STOP focus on the scale. ❗️ every day I get asked how much I weight, I don’t mind sharing but I don’t want my weight to be a number that someone else sees as some kind of ‘goal’ because weight doesn’t mean anything. A fit person will most likely weight more than a non fit person because muscles weight more than fat (volume) Instead, ask me how I feel 🤍

Focus on what you see in the mirror. 

- Do you see change? 
- Do you see the YOU, you want to see?
- Do you see a sparkle in your eyes?
- Do you see a smile on your face? 

(I only recommend using the scale to know where you start so you know how to calculate your macros, if that is what you want to do. Otherwise, throw that thing out today!)

🤍🤍🤍🤍
Answer is: I’m 6kgs heavier on the right but it doesn’t look like it - and that’s my point. 😇 weight is just a pointless number. Focus on how amazing you feel because I can guarantee you can look amazing at any weight. X

node.text:
For the longest time I was obsessed with achieving the ”3 bubbles” meaning Glutes, Hamstrings, Calves - in that size order - because I thought it looked sooo good and I felt embarrassed by having my calves and thighs being almost the same size. 

Although I am proud of achieving a goal of mine, I’m pretty tired of the whole ”you must be better” message that we’re constantly fed with. Either you want to lose weight or gain muscle or why are you even working out? Well, I work out to age better, to maintain my strength and muscles, for my health, for me. That’s it! Doesn’t have to be more complicated than that. 

Fitness isn’t a short term goal. It’s something we only benefit from when we have consistency through out our whole life. It will never go out of style to care for yourself. The best thing you can do for yourself is finding a workout style that you LIKE because then you will stick to it. If it’s weightlifting, running, riding a bike or all of them doesn’t matter. Maybe it was weightlifting but now you like cardio better, then do cardio! 

One thing does not have to exclude the other and you don’t have to constantly focus on what exercises are ’the most optimal’. Focus in the exercises that will make your body mind and soul smile today, tomorrow and forever. x 

This is something I’m so proud of with @athli.team! The support, the queens, the inspiration, the wholesomeness.
